title: A study of pre-equilibrium emission in alpha-induced reactions on 121,123Sb.

x4freetext: A study of pre-equilibrium emission in alpha-induced
reactions on 121,123Sb.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Canadian Journal of Physics, Vol.69, p.1376 (1991)

x4codes.hlp: Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre, Kolkata, India

x4freetext: Variable Energy Cyclotron Center,
Calcutta.
Energy degrading aluminium foils were used
to get the desired alpha-particle energy incident on
each foil.
The reaction cross section is determined
individually for each of emitted gamma rays and finally
their weighted average is taken.
Beam currents of the order of 100 nano-amperes
were used. the irradiation period was about 2 hours.
60-MeV diffused beam.
The flux of the a beam calculated from the
charge collected in the Faraday cup was
=8.47 x l10**11 (alpha particles/s/cm2.
A high-resolution 100 ml Ge(Li) detector coupled
to a multichannel analyzer was used. Detector was
calibrated using various standard gamma sources
including a 152Eu source..
Needed correction for dead time were included.
Natural antimony of spectroscopic purity better 99.9%
(natural abundance 121Sb = 57.3% and 123Sb = 42.7%)
was used for ma king the targets.
Targets were prepared using a vacuum evaporation
technique, to a thickness of 1mg/cm2 of antimony on
an aluminium backing of thickness 6.75 mg/cm2.
Preequilibrium model. Code "ACT" based on the
lines of code "STAPRE".
The authors do not give production yields on natural
target of antimony but deduced yield for separate
isotopes.
- The horizontal bars represent the energy
spread obtained from the energy loss in the actual
thickness of the foils as well as the inherent
uncertainty in the incident alpha-beam energy
Statistical errors are given on figs (the size
of the circle includes the magnitude of the statistical
errors if no error bar is plotted.)
Errors in the estimation of the number of
target nuclei and nonuniform deposition of sample.
Fluctuation in the beam current,
* Uncertainty of detector efficiency, straggling
effects may introduce certain errors but are neglected
because for alpha particles the energy straggling at
the end of the stack is always much smaller than the
energy loss of beam in the target foil itself.
The influence of low-energy neutrons is also negligible
Energy spread in the alpha-particle beam
facing each foil given as horizontal bars on figs.
By F.C.
Last checking has been done.
